{"term":"1973","caseName":"Gilmore v. City of Montgomery","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1973/72-1517","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 15, 1974","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/16685","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll hear arguments next in 72-1517, Georgia Theresa Gilmore against City of Montgomery.","start":0,"stop":57.377,"duration":57.38},{"text":"Mr. Levin, you may proceed whenever you're ready.","start":57.377,"stop":59.576,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":59.576,"stop":63.032,"duration":3.46},{"text":"This Civil Rights litigation comes before this Court on writ of certiorari to the United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit, and it follows a reversal in part and an affirmance in part of an opinion and an injunction issued by the United States District Court for the Middle District of Alabama.","start":63.032,"stop":83.839,"duration":20.81},{"text":"And although only two rather narrow issues remain for consideration by this Court, the litigation started out as a rather complex set of suits and motions which reigned at solving a problem of resegregation of public recreational facilities in Montgomery, Alabama.","start":83.839,"stop":102.657,"duration":18.82},{"text":"Prior to 1959, all public recreational facilities in Montgomery were segregated as a matter of law, as a matter of city ordinance.","start":102.657,"stop":112.31,"duration":9.65},{"text":"In 1959, the District Court of the Middle District in the initial Gilmore case, the first stage of this case, entered an order requiring desegregation of all public recreational facilities.","start":112.31,"stop":126.089,"duration":13.78},{"text":"Now, the city’s response to this order was to close all of the parks, all of the recreational facilities in the city.","start":126.089,"stop":133.18,"duration":7.09},{"text":"At about that same time, 1958-1959, the city first began to cooperate with the local private segregated YMCA by entering into a coordination agreement, turning over many public recreational programs to the YMCA.","start":133.18,"stop":152.281,"duration":19.1},{"text":"Other changes throughout the 60's and in the early 70's in the recreational programs of the city brought about a situation which the original Gilmore plaintiffs sought to correct.","start":152.281,"stop":163.718,"duration":11.44},{"text":"The desegregation of recreational facilities ordered in 1959 had been effectively negated, in our opinion, by increasing resegregation throughout the decade of the 60's.","start":163.718,"stop":177.183,"duration":13.47},{"text":"There were three interrelated suits and motions which were filed in order to try and do what could be done to undo what we term “resegregation.”","start":177.183,"stop":188.311,"duration":11.13},{"text":"First, in 1970 the District Court, in response to a complaint filed against the private YMCA, found that defendant to be conducting in concert with the city extensive segregated recreational programs.","start":188.311,"stop":204.998,"duration":16.69},{"text":"The court determined the YMCA was inseparable from the city itself and ordered desegregation of the YMCA. Second, in 1970, the present petitioners, in another aspect of the Gilmore case, reopened Gilmore alleging vast inequalities in the provision of public recreational facilities to blacks in the community when compared to what whites received.","start":204.998,"stop":234.026,"duration":29.03},{"text":"After one day of trial at which the court made a preliminary finding that, petitioners, plaintiffs then, had made a strong case or a strong showing of denial of equal protection.","start":234.026,"stop":245.214,"duration":11.19},{"text":"The city entered into an agreement which if followed would significantly and vastly improve recreational facilities in black neighborhoods in Montgomery.","start":245.214,"stop":256.358,"duration":11.14},{"text":"Third and finally, in 1972, the District Court entered the injunction, the order and opinion which really forms the basis of this particular stage of the litigation.","start":256.358,"stop":268.169,"duration":11.81},{"text":"There, the District Court said and actually issued a two-pronged injunction, enjoining the city from authorizing private segregated school use of public recreational facilities and also enjoining that same use by private segregated non-school clubs and organizations.","start":268.169,"stop":289.972,"duration":21.8},{"text":"The Fifth Circuit affirmed the segregated school aspect of the case only insofar as the use by the school proved to be what the Fifth Circuit termed an “exclusive use.”","start":289.972,"stop":302.666,"duration":12.69}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's most of that issue, isn't it?","start":302.666,"stop":305.363,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The exclusive use is entire issue.","start":305.363,"stop":307.093,"duration":1.73},{"text":"That is really what is before this Court as to schools.","start":307.093,"stop":311.088,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So that it is really a -- they today affirmed the District Court almost entirely with respect to schools, isn't that really?","start":311.088,"stop":321.183,"duration":10.09}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, with the exception of exclusive use, they infer -- they affirmed the District Court entirely.","start":321.183,"stop":325.764,"duration":4.58},{"text":"We consider exclusive use to be a major problem in the enforcement of this --","start":325.764,"stop":330.921,"duration":5.16}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but the Court of Appeals says they will -- that non-exclusive use by segregated academies should not be there, is that right?","start":330.921,"stop":340.047,"duration":9.13}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":340.047,"stop":341.173,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And so like they're going to the zoo?","start":341.173,"stop":344.103,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, first of all--","start":344.103,"stop":344.79,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Go in the park?","start":344.79,"stop":345.532,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know that going to a park or going to a zoo is recreational activity in the context of this particular case.","start":345.532,"stop":352.874,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, give me an example, give me an example (Voice Overlap) --","start":352.874,"stop":354.738,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, for example, I think if you were to look at the agreement that was actually entered into between the city and the YMCA in 19 --","start":354.738,"stop":363.261,"duration":8.52}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You can find out why this is a serious issue in the case at all, is it not?","start":363.261,"stop":366.332,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":366.332,"stop":366.588,"duration":0.26},{"text":"We believe it's a very serious issue and I think if you would look at the agreement that was entered into, which is in our reply brief, addendum page 134 (a).","start":366.588,"stop":374.99,"duration":8.4}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"When, what year?","start":374.99,"stop":376.65,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"This is 1965 when this became -- submitted into --","start":376.65,"stop":379.703,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the situation right now?","start":379.703,"stop":381.56,"duration":1.86},{"text":"What public facilities are available to the non-public schools and their students concerning which you complain?","start":381.56,"stop":390.372,"duration":8.81},{"text":"Could you just say 1, 2, 3, 4, what they are?","start":390.372,"stop":393.994,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I cannot because the only issue that the Fifth Circuit spoke directly to was private -- it was the private segregated school use of football fields, and then it said, “and similar uses” or something to that effect so that I don't know what other uses would be banned, would be forbidden.","start":393.994,"stop":413.72,"duration":19.73},{"text":"Presumably --","start":413.72,"stop":414.095,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's focus on the football fields and that's what you're challenging, that exclusion made by the Court of Appeals?","start":414.095,"stop":423.835,"duration":9.74}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We are challenging the exclusive use doctrine of the Court of Appeals.","start":423.835,"stop":427.894,"duration":4.06},{"text":"For example, if you get away from the football field factual situation which the Court of Appeals had before it, what do you do in a situation where there are six basketball courts available and the private segregated academy is only using one of the courts, is that an exclusive use?","start":427.894,"stop":443.939,"duration":16.05}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You're challenging a nonexclusive use doctrine in the sense that the segregated school should be barred from so-called nonexclusive use as well as exclusive use?","start":443.939,"stop":454.544,"duration":10.6}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But well, we're -- what we're trying to say is that exclusive use is not a definition that you can deal with in this situation. What you have to look to is whether or not your enhancing the program or the curriculum of the private segregated academy.","start":454.544,"stop":467.719,"duration":13.18},{"text":"And whether the exclusive -- the use is exclusive or nonexclusive is immaterial.","start":467.719,"stop":471.915,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Let's get back, Mr. Levin.","start":471.915,"stop":473.854,"duration":1.94},{"text":"As I understand it, these private segregated academies may not use public football fields?","start":473.854,"stop":480.426,"duration":6.57}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- that's correct, may not exclusively use a public football field.","start":480.426,"stop":484.43,"duration":4},{"text":"Now, may not exclusively use --","start":484.43,"stop":486.646,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought they couldn't use them at all, am I wrong?","start":486.646,"stop":488.916,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Exclusively.","start":488.916,"stop":489.92,"duration":1},{"text":"I --","start":489.92,"stop":490.348,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, not all of them.","start":490.348,"stop":491.731,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, presumably, since the Fifth Circuit says that exclusive use is the only use that is barred.","start":491.731,"stop":497.749,"duration":6.02},{"text":"Then, if you could figure a way to use a portion of the football field --","start":497.749,"stop":501.272,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if the public high schools -- if a nonsegregated public high schools use the football fields Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday, under this order, may a segregated academy use them on Friday?","start":501.272,"stop":515.434,"duration":14.16}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think -- I am not sure you have that in the order.","start":515.434,"stop":517.972,"duration":2.54},{"text":"I know, as a matter of fact, the city is not permitting that use.","start":517.972,"stop":520.284,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, maybe I haven't read that in the record.","start":520.284,"stop":522.993,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well I suppose, under the Court of Appeals' order, a segregated academy, a segregated academy team could play a nonsegregated academy team?","start":522.993,"stop":534.676,"duration":11.68}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Possibly so.","start":534.676,"stop":535.67,"duration":0.99},{"text":"The question-- what is exclusive use?","start":535.67,"stop":538.509,"duration":2.84},{"text":"You get right back to the problem of defining exclusive use.","start":538.509,"stop":540.805,"duration":2.3},{"text":"I might point out that the Fifth Circuit itself runs up against the problem because in a portion of the stipulation of facts submitted to the Fifth Circuit, one of the stipulations was to the effect, I do not have it right before me but it was to the effect that the -- that segregated -- there was no exclusive use.","start":540.805,"stop":565.774,"duration":24.97},{"text":"We stipulated that there was no exclusive use of these recreational facilities by private segregated academies and yet the Fifth Circuit’s own opinion upholds the injunction against segregated academy’s use of these football fields.","start":565.774,"stop":579.585,"duration":13.81},{"text":"It's -- we're saying it is an unworkable definition and that that is not the issue that you should look to.","start":579.585,"stop":585.132,"duration":5.55},{"text":"What one has to look to is whether or not this private segregated academy’s program, curriculum, whatever is being enhanced very, very much in the vain of the Norwood, of the Norwood case.","start":585.132,"stop":599.158,"duration":14.03},{"text":"Is the program being enhanced in some way by what the city service is being provided?","start":599.158,"stop":604.714,"duration":5.56}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me ask you a hypothetical relating to that.","start":604.714,"stop":607.102,"duration":2.39},{"text":"Suppose these were not matters of segregated schools, but suppose you had a Catholic academy run by the Catholic Order.","start":607.102,"stop":622.126,"duration":15.02},{"text":"Could, in your view, judicial power enjoin the city from letting the Catholic school play on that field because that had a tendency to enhance the operations of a church-operated school?","start":622.126,"stop":640.955,"duration":18.83}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":640.955,"stop":641.608,"duration":0.65},{"text":"I do not believe so, and I believe Your Honor spoke to that very kind of point in the Norwood case when you discussed the difference between religious activity which is, if I could be so bold as to say, considered generally to be a good activity.","start":641.608,"stop":656.48,"duration":14.87},{"text":"It's not something that's banned by the constitution.","start":656.48,"stop":659.473,"duration":2.99},{"text":"And the segregation is the activity which is something that is spoken directly to in the Thirteen and Fourteenth Amendments where, I hate to use a good and evil type definition, but that's essentially what I think this Court was saying in the Norwood case.","start":659.473,"stop":675.267,"duration":15.79},{"text":"And, however now a different situation might be presented if the school, for example, were a segregated Catholic academy.","start":675.267,"stop":681.974,"duration":6.71},{"text":"Then, the fact of its Catholicism would have no effect on the segregated aspect of the school.","start":681.974,"stop":688.469,"duration":6.5}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Levin, you were satisfied with the District Court order, weren't you?","start":688.469,"stop":692.786,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely, yes sir.","start":692.786,"stop":693.569,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now what is it the Court of Appeals allows that the District Court prohibited?","start":693.569,"stop":700.418,"duration":6.85}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The Court of Appeals allows nonexclusive use by private segregated academies of public recreational facilities.","start":700.418,"stop":710.005,"duration":9.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So what you object to is letting the private academies make use of any public facility where in your view its use contributes to the mission of the private academy?","start":710.005,"stop":727.42,"duration":17.41}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, but I think that it is important in this context to make note of the factual situation we find in Montgomery, Alabama.","start":727.42,"stop":734.87,"duration":7.45},{"text":"We’re not talking about any other section of the country or any other part of the country.","start":734.87,"stop":738.673,"duration":3.8},{"text":"We’re talking about a city that has a history of segregation and recreation, and I don’t want to get off into other public facilities because I don’t feel that that this case deals with other public facilities.","start":738.673,"stop":749.414,"duration":10.74},{"text":"It deals with public recreation facilities in Montgomery and there’s a unique factual background there.","start":749.414,"stop":756.54,"duration":7.13},{"text":"And I think that’s where the equal protection violations, if any, and we contend that they do, must be viewed from that point of view.","start":756.54,"stop":764.779,"duration":8.24}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now for example, if there is a public park, with six basketball courts, I gather, in your view the private academy should not be permitted to have, for example, one of its teams practice on one of those six courts?","start":764.779,"stop":779.387,"duration":14.61}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely.","start":779.387,"stop":780.208,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, now, but suppose just students who attend the private academy go and just have a pickup team to play them on the courts.","start":780.208,"stop":789.743,"duration":9.54},{"text":"Is that permitted?","start":789.743,"stop":790.999,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The issue there is completely different.","start":790.999,"stop":792.523,"duration":1.52},{"text":"We believe that what (Voice Overlap) --","start":792.523,"stop":793.175,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) Would you say that should be prohibited?","start":793.175,"stop":795.793,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Only if the activity is school initiated.","start":795.793,"stop":800.939,"duration":5.15},{"text":"If individual citizens --","start":800.939,"stop":801.317,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, my hypothetical was there was a bunch of kids, their school day is finished and they stop by and they want to have a pickup game (Voice Overlap).","start":801.317,"stop":809.705,"duration":8.39}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) that would indeed be a constitutional violation in and of itself to prohibit those children in a non-school connected capacity from using public recreational facilities.","start":809.705,"stop":819.152,"duration":9.45}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well a non-school connected then, that implies that it’s a part of the curriculum of the -- a course of instruction or something.","start":819.152,"stop":828.891,"duration":9.74}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Or program of the school.","start":828.891,"stop":829.834,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And if there’s any school program?","start":829.834,"stop":831.672,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":831.672,"stop":832.291,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And as part of the school program, it’s your view that that ought to be prohibited?","start":832.291,"stop":836.181,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":836.181,"stop":837.894,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Levin, your case is not restricted to schools here, is it?","start":837.894,"stop":842.374,"duration":4.48}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":842.374,"stop":842.563,"duration":0.19},{"text":"It is not restrict it to schools.","start":842.563,"stop":843.655,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me ask you a question then.","start":843.655,"stop":844.866,"duration":1.21},{"text":"Apart from the school background, suppose a group of Black Muslims wanted to have a picnic in the city park some Saturday morning, under the Court of Appeals decree, is this possible?","start":844.866,"stop":862.826,"duration":17.96}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Once again, granting that a picnic is recreational in the context of this case, which I really don’t believe it is, but let’s assume that it is, I suppose it would depend on whether or not Black Muslims close their membership to whites or do they have, under the rule that the District Court promulgated, do they have a policy of segregation in admissions.","start":862.826,"stop":886.055,"duration":23.23}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose they do and to get away from the picnic, suppose they wanted to use a basketball court?","start":886.055,"stop":894.179,"duration":8.12}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is a much better example because they were dealing strictly with recreational activities that had gone on in the past in this case.","start":894.179,"stop":901.075,"duration":6.9},{"text":"And in that situation, if you can’t apply the Fourteenth Amendment to segregated black groups, and I’m not at all 100% certain that you can, but if you can, then the black group with the policy of segregation in its admissions policy would be treated the same as a white group with the policy of segregation because the whole purpose of this series of lawsuits since 1959 has been to desegregate recreational facilities in Montgomery, Alabama.","start":901.075,"stop":933.521,"duration":32.45}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Levin, in the Court of Appeals opinion that is set out in your petition for certiorari and at page 13 (a) of the petitioner is a footnote to the Court of Appeals opinion, Footnote 12 --","start":933.521,"stop":947.103,"duration":13.58}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":947.103,"stop":947.647,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"-- where Judge Clark said the District Court made no findings about the history, frequency, or effects of public creation -- recreational facilities by such non-school affiliated private organizations.","start":947.647,"stop":960.539,"duration":12.89},{"text":"Furthermore, in this case which was tried on stipulated facts, nothing was stipulated which would support this prong of the injunction.","start":960.539,"stop":967.878,"duration":7.34},{"text":"I went back over the -- your motion for supplemental relief, your stipulation.","start":967.878,"stop":972.824,"duration":4.95},{"text":"The answer is to interact (Inaudible) would incline agree with Judge Clark’s observation and I would think if that’s the case, you never reach a constitutional question on your so-called second prong, the non-school related thing?","start":972.824,"stop":986.223,"duration":13.4}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The private class --","start":986.223,"stop":986.939,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"You simply -- the Fifth Circuit could’ve reversed that prong of the -- simply because the traditional grounds for an injunction, whether you got a constitutional violation or any other violation, are not made out?","start":986.939,"stop":998.316,"duration":11.38}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":998.316,"stop":998.692,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"What’s your answer to Judge Clark’s (Voice Overlap) --","start":998.692,"stop":999.943,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I recognize that problem.","start":999.943,"stop":1001.126,"duration":1.18},{"text":"I’d first like to point out that the court at the same appendix, 15 (a), made a finding which seems inconsistent with that Footnote that a period -- that there was a periodic and I quote, “a periodic use of recreational facilities by private clubs.”","start":1001.126,"stop":1016.439,"duration":15.31},{"text":"Now, there was evidence in the -- in all of the pleadings which the District Court considered, that is, the complaint, the answer, the motion which was a verified motion, there was evidence that all private -- that no one was excluded, but all private clubs and all private organizations were indeed permitted to use these --","start":1016.439,"stop":1034.079,"duration":17.64}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"But there was no showing, no indication at all as I read as to what the policies of these groups were with respect to whether or not they had open admissions or didn’t say much about it or what.","start":1034.079,"stop":1046.675,"duration":12.6},{"text":"That issue was really never focused on in your pleadings, I thought, or -- nor really by the District Courts?","start":1046.675,"stop":1051.733,"duration":5.06}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Much to the addendum to our reply brief deals with that very problem and we recognize this problem.","start":1051.733,"stop":1057.212,"duration":5.48}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"And your stipulation was to submit on the stipulation of facts, the answers to interrogatories in the pleadings without any reference to prior hearings in the case?","start":1057.212,"stop":1066.199,"duration":8.99}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think though that submitting on a stipulation of facts, which we of course did, and perhaps all of this is the result of an over familiarity by us as lawyers and by the court with this case because there's been so much litigation in the past few years.","start":1066.199,"stop":1079.496,"duration":13.3},{"text":"But the District Court did have before it, the District Court level, a great deal of evidence in the Gilmore case of 1970.","start":1079.496,"stop":1088.793,"duration":9.3},{"text":"That was the motion we filed on behalf of petitioners to equalize recreational facilities in the City of Montgomery, both blacks as well as whites.","start":1088.793,"stop":1098.85,"duration":10.06},{"text":"Now, I would like to point out before I get into that, and I do want to talk about what was before the court, that despite the Circuit Court’s contention that there was in -- that there were insufficient facts and evidence it nevertheless has now affected a rule of law which controls every District Court within its jurisdiction.","start":1098.85,"stop":1115.771,"duration":16.92}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1115.771,"stop":1117.217,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":1117.217,"stop":1118.011,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Didn’t Congress post the case on that?","start":1118.011,"stop":1121.187,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it did.","start":1121.187,"stop":1122.241,"duration":1.05},{"text":"That’s my understanding.","start":1122.241,"stop":1124.479,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) as a matter of law?","start":1124.479,"stop":1128.186,"duration":3.71}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I see.","start":1128.186,"stop":1129.218,"duration":1.03},{"text":"It finally set it as a matter of law, that the right of association was such an overwhelming right when compared to any right that -- to any Fourteenth Amendment violation.","start":1129.218,"stop":1141.061,"duration":11.84}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"It reached the constitutional.","start":1141.061,"stop":1142.788,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They reached the constitutional issue so we have this -- if there was never a fact in the case, we still have a rule of law that exists in the Fifth Circuit that we think needs correcting.","start":1142.788,"stop":1152.527,"duration":9.74}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"But wouldn’t it -- it wouldn’t exist if this court affirmed that prong of the Fifth Circuit’s judgment, not on the basis which the Fifth Circuit had, but on the grounds that no showing of an equitable nature was made out to support such an injunction?","start":1152.527,"stop":1168.026,"duration":15.5}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir, or as the petitioner's suggestion would be rather than that, that perhaps this is a situation where the District Court should have an opportunity to reexamine the factual situation on remand and it might turn out to be administratively burdensome, and that the District Court is going to make findings of fact based upon evidence that it did have before it that was not included to the record going to the Fifth Circuit --","start":1168.026,"stop":1190.575,"duration":22.55}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this too simple, Mr. Levin?","start":1190.575,"stop":1193.5,"duration":2.92},{"text":"What you think ought to be held here is that whether this is a private academy or a private club, social club, or anything else that, provided it has a problem of segregation, excluding Negroes, participation in its affairs that in that circumstance no public facility should be opened to a no -- public recreational facility should be opened to it for the furtherance of any program of that organization?","start":1193.5,"stop":1225.391,"duration":31.89}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be an accurate statement of our position.","start":1225.391,"stop":1227.458,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"How about art galleries?","start":1227.458,"stop":1229.585,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Once again, I don’t know that an art gallery has ever been an issue in any of these recreational cases.","start":1229.585,"stop":1233.86,"duration":4.27}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let’s suppose the academy -- the private segregated academy says that on Saturday morning or Friday afternoon the third and the fourth grades will all go to the gallery as part of our enhancing -- your appreciation of art.","start":1233.86,"stop":1254.763,"duration":20.9},{"text":"So they can’t get in?","start":1254.763,"stop":1257.177,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think this, and again this is a little bit away from the recreational area that in my opinion, aside from this case that they should not be permitted to use because it is an enhancement of the curriculum of the school and it is a school-oriented, school-initiated program.","start":1257.177,"stop":1270.434,"duration":13.26},{"text":"It’s a vast benefit to the school.","start":1270.434,"stop":1273.822,"duration":3.39},{"text":"It is certainly something that the school should not be permitted to --","start":1273.822,"stop":1276.548,"duration":2.73}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a benefit to school or benefit to students?","start":1276.548,"stop":1279.737,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It’s a benefit to the school.","start":1279.737,"stop":1280.777,"duration":1.04},{"text":"It enhances the school.","start":1280.777,"stop":1281.682,"duration":0.9},{"text":"It makes the parents --","start":1281.682,"stop":1282.678,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Each of the benefit (Inaudible)","start":1282.678,"stop":1284.596,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we have suggested two possible --","start":1284.596,"stop":1286.812,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The sewage system and lighting system.","start":1286.812,"stop":1289.259,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We have suggested two possible exceptions.","start":1289.259,"stop":1291.216,"duration":1.96},{"text":"One, Justice Rehnquist -- Mr. Justice Rehnquist promulgated in Moose Lodge case that is, necessities of life and that that was once again mentioned in Norwood and the other is any bar that might totally ban the existence of the school within -- in the lines of something -- in the lines on Pierce versus Society of Sisters.","start":1291.216,"stop":1315.074,"duration":23.86},{"text":"Those are arguably exceptions and streets, public sidewalks, sewage facilities, those all come within it, I think, at least the necessities of life exception that we suggested.","start":1315.074,"stop":1328.881,"duration":13.81}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you really distinguish recreation from culture in this context, that is, the art gallery, the symphony concerts?","start":1328.881,"stop":1337.387,"duration":8.51},{"text":"Suppose, for example, the city maintained or engaged a symphony orchestra to come and play or a ballet and they issued free tickets to all the students of public schools, but refused to issue free tickets to students attending private schools.","start":1337.387,"stop":1353.266,"duration":15.88},{"text":"Do you think no equal protection question would arise there?","start":1353.266,"stop":1356.844,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that’s very much like the Norwood case where you issue free -- where you free -- issue free textbooks to all students in public schools, but not free textbooks to --","start":1356.844,"stop":1364.112,"duration":7.27}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the textbooks are not quite like art galleries and theaters because other people and students use them.","start":1364.112,"stop":1370.709,"duration":6.6},{"text":"These are public facilities I’m talking about, open to the public generally.","start":1370.709,"stop":1374.956,"duration":4.25},{"text":"But under the hypothesis of my question, the students in the private schools would be excluded because they were students in private school?","start":1374.956,"stop":1386.052,"duration":11.1}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Because they were students in private segregated schools and because the permission to use these facilities would enhance the school itself and would be of great benefit to it.","start":1386.052,"stop":1398.122,"duration":12.07}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But as I understand it, you don’t go so far as to say that the school children should be barred to use of the public streets to get back and forth to the private school, the private segregated school?","start":1398.122,"stop":1407.269,"duration":9.15}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1407.269,"stop":1407.678,"duration":0.41},{"text":"We have specifically written to that several times in or at least tried to in the purpose of --","start":1407.678,"stop":1411.64,"duration":3.96}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"How about lunch programs?","start":1411.64,"stop":1413.483,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Lunch programs, I don’t see any distinction between lunch programs and textbooks.","start":1413.483,"stop":1421.54,"duration":8.06},{"text":"That may be the most analogous situation.","start":1421.54,"stop":1423.213,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean even free milk?","start":1423.213,"stop":1426.677,"duration":3.46}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We’re getting far afield from recreational facilities, but --","start":1426.677,"stop":1429.88,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I’m not sure that they may -- they may not be recreational facilities, but don’t we have to find something (Voice Overlap) --","start":1429.88,"stop":1434.428,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I could not draw a distinction.","start":1434.428,"stop":1436.074,"duration":1.65},{"text":"I could not draw a distinction between the milk situation and the textbook situation.","start":1436.074,"stop":1441.842,"duration":5.77},{"text":"That’s available from another source.","start":1441.842,"stop":1443.179,"duration":1.34},{"text":"You can buy milk from another source.","start":1443.179,"stop":1444.23,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"How about inoculation against contagious diseases?","start":1444.23,"stop":1447.243,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Might well come be under the --","start":1447.243,"stop":1449.075,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We’ll pick up at that point in the morning.","start":1449.075,"stop":1454.669,"duration":5.59}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 16, 1974","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/16723","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We’ll resume arguments in Number 1517, and Mr. Levin, I think you have about seven minutes remaining.","start":0,"stop":17.099,"duration":17.1}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":17.099,"stop":20.941,"duration":3.84},{"text":"I have only two further points that I’d like to make with respect to this case.","start":20.941,"stop":27.927,"duration":6.99},{"text":"We have provided the Court with an addendum to petitioners’ reply brief which is some 152 pages in length.","start":27.927,"stop":37.519,"duration":9.59},{"text":"Now, all of this evidence found in this addendum was introduced in Judge Johnson’s court in the District Court in the 1970 phase of the Gilmore case.","start":37.519,"stop":46.878,"duration":9.36},{"text":"That’s the phase that dealt with equalization of public recreational facilities in Montgomery.","start":46.878,"stop":52.15,"duration":5.27},{"text":"This present litigation, that is this motion for supplemental relief in the Gilmore case, was initiated less than eight months after the order of the court approving the agreement between the petitioners and the city in that Gilmore case.","start":52.15,"stop":68.274,"duration":16.12},{"text":"These facts are material because they were before Judge Johnson by virtue of his authority to take judicial notice of his own court records, and because the testimony therein would have clearly supported the injunction with respect to private segregated clubs and organizations used of public recreational facilities.","start":68.274,"stop":88.258,"duration":19.98},{"text":"I think the keyword in examining these facts is “shift.”","start":88.258,"stop":94.377,"duration":6.12},{"text":"There was a shift of white recreational programs which were formally in the province solely of the city and the recreation department to private clubs and organizations.","start":94.377,"stop":104.798,"duration":10.42},{"text":"So the city maintained control only over the black recreational programs.","start":104.798,"stop":110.335,"duration":5.54},{"text":"Now Mayor James himself, at the addendum page 19 (a), who was the mayor at the time that all these went on, admitted that the YMCA City Coordination Agreement which we discussed yesterday, and this is a quote, controlled, quote, “Not only the YMCA but also the Boy’s Club and all of the others.”","start":110.335,"stop":129.632,"duration":19.3},{"text":"So, the shift was not only to the segregated YMCA, but in the Addendum 7588 4a you’ll see it was to a white Babe Ruth League, to a white Dixie Youth League parallel to Little League which was a Black League, to the White City Club Softball teams, and to the White Church League Softball teams.","start":129.632,"stop":147.891,"duration":18.26},{"text":"These private segregated clubs are making use of public recreational facilities, extensive use.","start":147.891,"stop":154.2,"duration":6.31},{"text":"The result is a resegregation of recreational facilities in Montgomery.","start":154.2,"stop":159.876,"duration":5.68},{"text":"And even if one ignores the specific finding in Smith versus YMCA, that this was done with the intent to avoid desegregation of public recreational facilities, certainly, the foreseeable result of these activities would’ve been to resegregate those facilities.","start":159.876,"stop":175.511,"duration":15.63},{"text":"I’d like to make one final comment on exclusive use which we discussed with respect to the private segregated school situation yesterday, and that is that it’s not simply some abstract theory that the Fifth Circuit discussed in support of a legal doctrine.","start":175.511,"stop":190.11,"duration":14.6},{"text":"The District Court was specifically instructed to include the Exclusive Use Doctrine in its new injunction on remand, and this it did and that’s found at page 29 (a) of the appendix.","start":190.11,"stop":200.784,"duration":10.67}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose that reflects the judicial practice of this Court following Brown versus Board of Education entering orders, making parks and like public places open to members of the minority races.","start":200.784,"stop":223.659,"duration":22.88}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I’m not sure what Your Honor means.","start":223.659,"stop":226.15,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Because that you’ve been -- the (Inaudible) you were born, we had cases here involving the park or swimming pool or -- a racial minority couldn’t go to play baseball or walk or have a picnic or a swim and our decrees in those cases as I remember merely prevent the city from barring in from --","start":226.15,"stop":258.199,"duration":32.05}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Excluding racial minorities.","start":258.199,"stop":261.356,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"And I suppose that’s reflected in the Court of Appeals’ approach.","start":261.356,"stop":270.288,"duration":8.93},{"text":"Up to that time, many of the parks in some areas of the country get -- have been turned over exclusively, you know to the dominant race.","start":270.288,"stop":281.191,"duration":10.9}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course that was the same situation that existed in Montgomery in 1959 when the initial Gilmore case was brought.","start":281.191,"stop":288.113,"duration":6.92},{"text":"However, the Fifth Circuit, as best I recall, did not discuss, that may have been an underlying reason but it was not discussed in the opinion, and exclusive use seem to be directed more at ensuring that individual students or individual citizens did not become subjected to an exclusion from public recreational facilities.","start":288.113,"stop":308.896,"duration":20.78},{"text":"But of course, the District Court’s order never -- there’s nothing in the District Court’s order which would’ve done that anyhow and that was why I couldn’t understand the reason for the exclusive use doctrine being incorporated into a -- in the Fifth Circuit’s opinion.","start":308.896,"stop":325.903,"duration":17.01},{"text":"I think that as a matter of law, that it’s erroneous but it is the law in the Fifth Circuit now.","start":325.903,"stop":331.33,"duration":5.43}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright, well, I think, historically, it was the practice that this Court in its early decisions on recreational facilities that the Fifth Circuit struck down.","start":331.33,"stop":345.505,"duration":14.18},{"text":"It’s not exclusive.","start":345.505,"stop":346.462,"duration":0.96},{"text":"It’s everybody.","start":346.462,"stop":347.995,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree.","start":347.995,"stop":348.818,"duration":0.82},{"text":"With the exception of private segregate -- when you’re assisting private segregated schools and thereby detracting from the public school system in a peculiar situation that you have in the south and in Montgomery then of course, you enter into another area where you can’t give support.","start":348.818,"stop":363.066,"duration":14.25},{"text":"You can’t enhance the programs of these private segregated academies.","start":363.066,"stop":367.049,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if I understood you correctly yesterday counsel, and perhaps this could be cleared up.","start":367.049,"stop":372.477,"duration":5.43},{"text":"If five or six young men or 11 young men came down individually to play football or volleyball or whatever, they could come in.","start":372.477,"stop":383.515,"duration":11.04},{"text":"But if they came down in the uniforms of the private school playing in connection with an intramural athletic program, they could not use the facility, is that right?","start":383.515,"stop":396.795,"duration":13.28}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not if it were a school-initiated activity.","start":396.795,"stop":400.833,"duration":4.04},{"text":"Individually, there's no difficulty and we’ve never -- certainly, we never make any attempt to keep any citizen out of public recreational facilities.","start":400.833,"stop":407.458,"duration":6.63},{"text":"That’s never been the point, but as a school-initiated program either curriculum or athletic program, it would be prohibited under our theory of the case.","start":407.458,"stop":420.306,"duration":12.85}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Counsel, I think that the District Court would’ve barred the exclusive use of public recreation facilities by any private club that had an express discriminatory policy and the Court of Appeals reversed that.","start":420.306,"stop":438.671,"duration":18.37}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It would've -- the District Court would have barred the use.","start":438.671,"stop":440.389,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":440.389,"stop":442.241,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"By a private segregated club and the Fifth Circuit reversed that in full.","start":442.241,"stop":446.119,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"In full and the effect of that is that a private club with an express discriminatory policy may use public recreation facilities?","start":446.119,"stop":455.046,"duration":8.93}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":455.046,"stop":458.034,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Whether exclusive or nonexclusive?","start":458.034,"stop":459.967,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph J. Levin, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s correct.","start":459.967,"stop":463.138,"duration":3.17},{"text":"Well, I see my time is up, if there are no further questions.","start":463.138,"stop":466.985,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well, Mr. Levin.","start":466.985,"stop":470.34,"duration":3.35},{"text":"Mr. Phelps.","start":470.34,"stop":472.34,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":472.34,"stop":475.434,"duration":3.09},{"text":"At the outset, I’d like to clarify just a little bit concerning the record in the case and specifically the reply brief that the petitioners filed last week in which they attach depositions or parts or parts of depositions as addendum.","start":475.434,"stop":494.227,"duration":18.79},{"text":"Now, these depositions were taken, as Mr. Levin pointed out, in 1970.","start":494.227,"stop":500.109,"duration":5.88},{"text":"I think may -- it may be well to go in and look at the sequence or chronology of this case.","start":500.109,"stop":507.93,"duration":7.82},{"text":"It was -- original complaint, as pointed out by Mr. Levin, was December 28, 1958 or order posed in the case by the District Court on April 22, 1964.","start":507.93,"stop":519.193,"duration":11.26},{"text":"Then in 1970, on August 12, 1970, the petitioners filed a motion to cite for contempt and for relief.","start":519.193,"stop":528.103,"duration":8.91},{"text":"And in that August 12, 1970 motion they did raise the issue of this resegregation.","start":528.103,"stop":534.577,"duration":6.47},{"text":"They raised the issue of the YMCA case which been decided a month before.","start":534.577,"stop":539.819,"duration":5.24},{"text":"It was pursuant to that hearing that these depositions were taken or it was pursuant to that motion that these depositions were taken.","start":539.819,"stop":546.91,"duration":7.09},{"text":"And that case resulted in the joint filing of a plan for extensive improvement of recreational facilities throughout the city.","start":546.91,"stop":555.716,"duration":8.81},{"text":"Montgomery, as many other communities, we had recreation facilities in one part of town that weren't as good as another.","start":555.716,"stop":562.874,"duration":7.16},{"text":"Some in the black community, one is good as some of the white.","start":562.874,"stop":566.229,"duration":3.36},{"text":"Some in -- some portions of the white, one is good in some portions as the black, but be that as it may, the city, by a joint motion agreed to equalize all facilities.","start":566.229,"stop":575.61,"duration":9.38},{"text":"We had just finished a community center at the time the filing of the petition.","start":575.61,"stop":579.474,"duration":3.86},{"text":"It was completed about that time in a lower income in Negro area.","start":579.474,"stop":583.288,"duration":3.81},{"text":"But be that as it may, we say facilities ought to be as good as we can possibly make them all over town, we agreed to do that and Judge Johnson approved this plan and found that was dispositive of all the issues before the court.","start":583.288,"stop":597.297,"duration":14.01},{"text":"And that was in December of 1971 when the District Court said that the joint plan disposed of all issues before the court, and that appears in the appendix, in the very outset when the chronology of the case is set forth.","start":597.297,"stop":612.964,"duration":15.67},{"text":"Then, far than that and after all those issues were disposed of in September of 1971, the petitioners came along and filed a petition for supplemental relief and that’s the basic -- basis of this present proceeding.","start":612.964,"stop":626.725,"duration":13.76},{"text":"Now, the basis for the supplemental relief was largely, and I think, a fair reading of it discloses that it dealt with private schools and private academies.","start":626.725,"stop":637.047,"duration":10.32},{"text":"Let’s go for a moment and look at the depositions that Mr. Levin attaches to his reply brief, and he includes, and I think very significantly, in this case.","start":637.047,"stop":648.929,"duration":11.88},{"text":"If you look back at those depositions, I skip from page 20 to page 40, in some instances and a whole lot of them are omitted.","start":648.929,"stop":656.137,"duration":7.21},{"text":"Now, we didn’t have enough -- he didn’t designate these as part of his appendix and, of course, we had no opportunity to counter designate so we have had delivered to the Clerk’s Office the entire deposition.","start":656.137,"stop":667.474,"duration":11.34},{"text":"And, we’ve asked the court if they deem these depositions -- if the court deems these depositions appropriate before the court, all of them should certainly be considered.","start":667.474,"stop":675.059,"duration":7.58},{"text":"For example, he talks about segregated Babe Ruth, but on page 15 of a deposition of Mr. McKean and he omitted this from the part he put back in this addendum.","start":675.059,"stop":685.643,"duration":10.58},{"text":"As far as Babe Ruth is specific in here, it says no distinction be made between black and white, absolutely not.","start":685.643,"stop":692.324,"duration":6.68},{"text":"There has never been any distinction in as far as Babe Ruth Leagues, nationally or from the state, no distinction with regard to race.","start":692.324,"stop":699.471,"duration":7.15},{"text":"That’s omitted from what he’s got here, but we have delivered it to the Clerk’s Office.","start":699.471,"stop":703.261,"duration":3.79},{"text":"Mr. McKean said they put out notices at all schools for children who want to play Babe Ruth or boys who want to play Babe Ruth to come and attend.","start":703.261,"stop":710.78,"duration":7.52},{"text":"Dixie Youth, he mentioned that this morning, he mentioned that in his addendum.","start":710.78,"stop":714.287,"duration":3.51},{"text":"He attached some depositions of a Mr. Marshall, but he didn’t attach them all.","start":714.287,"stop":717.797,"duration":3.51},{"text":"And the parts that he didn’t attach say this on page 16, “No restriction against Blacks playing.","start":717.797,"stop":723.867,"duration":6.07},{"text":"All Dixie Youth Leagues invite black boys to come out.","start":723.867,"stop":726.929,"duration":3.06},{"text":"No boy is excluded because of race.”","start":726.929,"stop":729.583,"duration":2.65},{"text":"Leagues formed on a geographic population basis in which black neighborhoods and communities are included on page 26, page 30.","start":729.583,"stop":736.391,"duration":6.81},{"text":"Blacks are in fact, in all Dixie Youth teams.","start":736.391,"stop":739.147,"duration":2.76},{"text":"On page 30, solicitation done for Dixie Youth in black neighborhoods.","start":739.147,"stop":743.273,"duration":4.13},{"text":"Page 32, for the coming year, more blacks were urged and hopefully would come out and in point of fact, they did.","start":743.273,"stop":751.659,"duration":8.39},{"text":"In point of fact, Babe Ruth Leagues, athlete -- athletics in Montgomery, Alabama and throughout the State of Alabama encouraged participation by all people without regard to race or color.","start":751.659,"stop":764.988,"duration":13.33},{"text":"Alabama, as a matter of fact, is proud of the Black athletes.","start":764.988,"stop":770.248,"duration":5.26},{"text":"They play for our colleges throughout the state.","start":770.248,"stop":773.252,"duration":3},{"text":"The University of Alabama, for example, has many, many black players on the starting basketball team that played the University of Mississippi the other night.","start":773.252,"stop":780.357,"duration":7.11},{"text":"But be that as it may, the depositions that he attaches here are not complete and these were submitted in August 1970 prior to the plaintiffs and the city agreeing on this joint plan for improvement.","start":780.357,"stop":794.18,"duration":13.82},{"text":"Why were they able to agree on the joint plan for improvement and not go into the issue of “resegregation” in their disposing of all issues?","start":794.18,"stop":801.212,"duration":7.03},{"text":"I submit to you that the depositions that were all filed in the District Court, and were left up high over from what he sends up here, establish why they did that, because they saw that there was no distinction in this Babe Ruth, Little League, or anywhere else.","start":801.212,"stop":818.334,"duration":17.12},{"text":"As far as the City of Montgomery is concerned, he attaches a deposition -- parts of a deposition from a Mr. Boldman.","start":818.334,"stop":825.715,"duration":7.38},{"text":"What he doesn’t attach shows that there is integrative participation in public recreation throughout the spectrum of Montgomery Alabama.","start":825.715,"stop":832.493,"duration":6.78},{"text":"Football, basketball, baseball are integrated.","start":832.493,"stop":835.557,"duration":3.06},{"text":"You have integrated teams playing integrated teams and predominantly white playing predominantly black throughout on page 49, 50, and 56 of Mr. Boldman’s deposition which, significantly, he didn’t attach.","start":835.557,"stop":847.275,"duration":11.72},{"text":"So we think, first, that the issues -- all which --","start":847.275,"stop":850.166,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Phelps, I’m sorry, I don’t know that I follow you.","start":850.166,"stop":852.882,"duration":2.72},{"text":"Are you -- is this an argument that this case has already been settled between the parties?","start":852.882,"stop":856.688,"duration":3.81}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":856.688,"stop":857.106,"duration":0.42},{"text":"It -- it's an argument that the depositions that he refers to are establish that the City of Montgomery does not discriminate in recreational activities and programs because of race or color and it is an argument too, sir, that this was before the District Court in 1970 when the District Court approved a joint motion for improvement.","start":857.106,"stop":881.273,"duration":24.17},{"text":"The issue was before the court on this alleged resegregation.","start":881.273,"stop":885.411,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well and yet, the District Court entered the injunction that then was modified or reversed, as you plead, by the Court of Appeals?","start":885.411,"stop":893.523,"duration":8.11}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":893.523,"stop":893.864,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Notwithstanding this -- all this material was before the District Court in 1970?","start":893.864,"stop":897.999,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"The District Court in the order forming the basis of this appeal, if it please the Court, ever made no finding of resegregation and we are saying to the court that the reason he made no finding of resegregation is because, in point of fact, there was none.","start":897.999,"stop":914.828,"duration":16.83},{"text":"He said this, “When there joint improvement petition was approved.”","start":914.828,"stop":918.819,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, on what then do the rest of the injunction, Judge Johnson?","start":918.819,"stop":925.117,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"I think he rested the injunction on the fact that the pure simple fact that an all-white private school should not be able to use a municipal facility, one and then secondly on the issue of private organizations, without resegregation, private organizations shouldn’t use municipal facilities if they have a racially discriminatory admissions policy.","start":925.117,"stop":951.923,"duration":26.81},{"text":"I don’t think, in the point I’m hoping to make and maybe I’m not doing it too clearly here, is that the issue of resegregation was not part of the District Court’s order.","start":951.923,"stop":961.576,"duration":9.65},{"text":"It was not part of the District Court’s order.","start":961.576,"stop":963.889,"duration":2.31},{"text":"The District Court in the order, they formed the basis of this writ, found that the city made facilities available to all on a non-discriminatory basis.","start":963.889,"stop":975.093,"duration":11.2},{"text":"When he had these depositions before him back in 1970, what did he say when we filed a joint motions for improvement?","start":975.093,"stop":984.416,"duration":9.32},{"text":"The District Court said it further appears that the implementation of said agreement and plans would dispose of all of the issues involved in this litigation and what were those issues?","start":984.416,"stop":994.532,"duration":10.12},{"text":"Those issues included the issue of this alleged --","start":994.532,"stop":998,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- are you suggesting, Mr. Phelps, that in light of that finding that is in itself enough to suggest error in the injunction he granted?","start":998,"stop":1009.758,"duration":11.76}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1009.758,"stop":1010.446,"duration":0.69},{"text":"I think that tells us this.","start":1010.446,"stop":1012.812,"duration":2.37},{"text":"Mr. Levin, and on his brief, reply brief and in this court, contends that there has been type of a resegregation.","start":1012.812,"stop":1021.392,"duration":8.58},{"text":"He says the District Court is bound to have known that.","start":1021.392,"stop":1024.347,"duration":2.95},{"text":"We state to you that the District Court knew to the contrary because of the fortunes of the testimony that was already before him.","start":1024.347,"stop":1031.068,"duration":6.72},{"text":"He knew, to the contrary, resegregation didn’t enter into it as --","start":1031.068,"stop":1035.04,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, my problem Mr. Phelps, I’m not following it.","start":1035.04,"stop":1039.664,"duration":4.62},{"text":"I don’t quite understand, assuming that this is all quite so and that indeed there was no question of resegregation, nevertheless, the District Court entered the injunction?","start":1039.664,"stop":1051.714,"duration":12.05}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right, sir.","start":1051.714,"stop":1052.829,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"On what basis?","start":1052.829,"stop":1054.147,"duration":1.32},{"text":"On what was it predicated?","start":1054.147,"stop":1055.397,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it was predicated on the District Court’s feelings and understanding of the law that because a private club had a racially discriminatory admission policy, that private club should not be permitted to use a public recreational facility.","start":1055.397,"stop":1071.686,"duration":16.29},{"text":"I do not believe that the District Court intended to imply by that, that the city was guilty of any evasion of a prior court order.","start":1071.686,"stop":1080.357,"duration":8.67},{"text":"As Judge Clark pointed out on Footnote 14 in the Circuit Court opinion, this case does not involve any evasion of the city responsibility to operate recreational facilities on a desegregated basis by the subterfuges converting such facilities to private control.","start":1080.357,"stop":1097.316,"duration":16.96},{"text":"The District Court had been presented with substance for that finding and even the plaintiffs themselves in the Fifth Circuit, on page 12 of their brief in the Fifth Circuit, took the position in the Fifth Circuit agree to neutrality on behalf of the city.","start":1097.316,"stop":1114.698,"duration":17.38},{"text":"The fact that the state officials have presented a racially neutral policy and that the actual discrimination has occurred at the hands of private individuals, has never been viewed by the courts as a significant factor in determining the constitutionality of state action.","start":1114.698,"stop":1127.945,"duration":13.25},{"text":"Mr. Justice Brennan, the purpose of my going into this was that that this matter that we are here today on was not tried before the District Court on an issue of resegregation.","start":1127.945,"stop":1139.059,"duration":11.11},{"text":"It was not presented to the Circuit Court of Appeals on an issue of resegregation.","start":1139.059,"stop":1143.62,"duration":4.56},{"text":"We submit to you that it could not have been because such is not defect, and we don’t go out in thin air and just say that without support.","start":1143.62,"stop":1151.629,"duration":8.01},{"text":"We say it is not the fact because the depositions that were actually before the District Court, as Mr. Levin pointed out earlier, when this issue was raised, they asked more than just improvement in August 1970.","start":1151.629,"stop":1164.657,"duration":13.03},{"text":"They asked for contempt and they asked that we would be enjoined from allowing these private groups to do it.","start":1164.657,"stop":1170.675,"duration":6.02},{"text":"The District Court didn’t order that.","start":1170.675,"stop":1172,"duration":1.33},{"text":"He approved the improvement of the facilities without finding, as Mr. -- Judge Clark said, “Any involvement of the city’s responsibility.”","start":1172,"stop":1180.897,"duration":8.9},{"text":"And --","start":1180.897,"stop":1181.011,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Phelps, what’s your position with respect to the Footnote 12 in Judge Clark’s opinion?","start":1181.011,"stop":1186.744,"duration":5.73},{"text":"The Court of Appeals saying that the District Court made no findings about history, frequency, or effects of public recreational facility used by such non-school affiliated organizations?","start":1186.744,"stop":1198.014,"duration":11.27},{"text":"The case was tried on stipulated facts.","start":1198.014,"stop":1200.031,"duration":2.02},{"text":"Nothing was stipulated which would support this prong of the injunction.","start":1200.031,"stop":1203.894,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"I think Judge Clark is correct, sir and I think the posture of the case is -- was it -- as it was presented to the Court of Appeals then the District Court is such, that you really could never do it.","start":1203.894,"stop":1213.595,"duration":9.7},{"text":"They asked for a broad spectrum on all the effect in every private club of every nature if they got a discriminatory admission clause.","start":1213.595,"stop":1221.471,"duration":7.88},{"text":"How would you ever be able to go into the history, frequency, or effects of more than 100 and it’s literally hundreds of private organizations that use municipal facilities.","start":1221.471,"stop":1234.296,"duration":12.83}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I understand Judge Clark, he is saying, you know even if you could have done that or even if you could have done it by a representative sampling, in fact, they didn’t do it in this case, neither you nor your opponents?","start":1234.296,"stop":1248.11,"duration":13.81}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"It wasn’t done in this case.","start":1248.11,"stop":1249.478,"duration":1.37},{"text":"It was presented to the District Court on a -- stipulated facts that all of the facilities were open to all on a non-discriminatory basis.","start":1249.478,"stop":1260.929,"duration":11.45},{"text":"Now, I don’t think that this case is the proper vehicle to go down and have a blanket order in Montgomery, Alabama applying to all types of private clubs regardless of their size, regardless of the purpose, regardless of the frequency or use, a blanket order is what Judge Clark says that the -- was too broad, and I think that that’s well supported by the law.","start":1260.929,"stop":1285.08,"duration":24.15},{"text":"I think we can’t speculate, we can’t guess about the involvement going on.","start":1285.08,"stop":1291.186,"duration":6.11},{"text":"I don’t believe that’s what the -- this Court envisioned in Burton and I think, as this Court said in Norwood, you can’t just assume that all of these things are invidious and that’s what they ask in this case as an order, a blanket order saying any club with a discriminatory admission policies can’t use municipal facilities.","start":1291.186,"stop":1312.795,"duration":21.61},{"text":"We --","start":1312.795,"stop":1312.918,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Wouldn’t it -- well, this -- did this order we have here arose from a supplemental petition in a case that had been within the -- filed in the District Court?","start":1312.918,"stop":1323.91,"duration":10.99}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1323.91,"stop":1325.374,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And in the original order in 19’59 was that the city was segregating in its recreational policies?","start":1325.374,"stop":1334.595,"duration":9.22}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"The 1959 order ordered all facilities opened up.","start":1334.595,"stop":1337.706,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1337.706,"stop":1338.274,"duration":0.57},{"text":"In fact, but if you a -- wouldn’t the best counter is that part of that order, as an effective remedy to say that private clubs couldn’t use if they were discriminatory -- if they had a discriminatory policy could not use city made recreational facilities?","start":1338.274,"stop":1353.484,"duration":15.21}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"I don’t believe so, Mr. Justice White, and I feel strongly that it would not have been for several reasons.","start":1353.484,"stop":1359.915,"duration":6.43},{"text":"One, I the -- I don’t believe that the city is under an affirmative duty to require desegregation in private clubs.","start":1359.915,"stop":1369.478,"duration":9.56},{"text":"And, secondly, these private clubs, as pointed out by the Court of Appeals, are entitled we think now, as well as then in the periodic use of public facilities.","start":1369.478,"stop":1381.985,"duration":12.51},{"text":"They wouldn’t found here and they simply would --","start":1381.985,"stop":1384.471,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't -- did Judge Johnson ever articulate any reasons or basis for entering this supplemental injunction that included this prohibition against use by Judge Johnson?","start":1384.471,"stop":1397.993,"duration":13.52}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1397.993,"stop":1399.547,"duration":1.55},{"text":"As Judge Clark commented, no findings were made on any evasion of the city’s responsibility.","start":1399.547,"stop":1406.208,"duration":6.66},{"text":"There weren't any findings that this private clubs were a place -- a public accommodation or any nexus between the private clubs and the municipality.","start":1406.208,"stop":1414.5,"duration":8.29}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Phelps, you said that returning to resegregation was not the issue before Judge Johnson.","start":1414.5,"stop":1421.04,"duration":6.54},{"text":"What was the issue?","start":1421.04,"stop":1422.623,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"The issue before Judge Johnson, Mr. Justice Marshall, was whether or not just because a club has admission policy that doesn’t -- it excludes either whites or blacks, whether that in and of itself would preclude that organization from the use of municipal facilities.","start":1422.623,"stop":1439.764,"duration":17.14}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And that’s what is before us now?","start":1439.764,"stop":1441.42,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"As I under it, Mr. Justice Marshall, that is the question before you.","start":1441.42,"stop":1445.719,"duration":4.3},{"text":"I would like --","start":1445.719,"stop":1446.175,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Your task here, Mr. Phelps, if I may say so, is to defend that judgment of the Court of Appeals, isn’t it?","start":1446.175,"stop":1455.578,"duration":9.4}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1455.578,"stop":1456.221,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"The modification of Judge Johnson’s order and I think perhaps some of us have been confused as to why this background, or how it related closely at least to the modification made by the Court of Appeals?","start":1456.221,"stop":1471.929,"duration":15.71}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"The background, sir was necessitated or I thought it was because of this reply brief that they filed last week in which they attached only portions of some depositions, and I thought it appropriate to call to the attention of the Court that there was a great deal more that was brought out even back then that he didn’t see fit to include and that was the purpose of my going into that portion of the background.","start":1471.929,"stop":1494.274,"duration":22.34}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Phelps, may I come back to this paragraph 3 of Judge Johnson’s order that says that -- that refers to the use of these facilities by any private group, club, or organization.","start":1494.274,"stop":1509.984,"duration":15.71},{"text":"Is there any definition in the record anywhere of a club or an organization or a group?","start":1509.984,"stop":1516.292,"duration":6.31}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1516.292,"stop":1517.72,"duration":1.43},{"text":"I think --","start":1517.72,"stop":1518.226,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Would this embrace a lady’s bridge club?","start":1518.226,"stop":1521.385,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"I think this would -- if Your Honor please would embrace the spectrum from Muslim to Mormon with Lion’s Club and City Club and ladies garden clubs and bridge clubs and just everybody, from a group of 5-500.","start":1521.385,"stop":1537.763,"duration":16.38},{"text":"It would embrace the Moose Lodge, the Fraters, every conceivable type of private club, political, social, fraternal, charitable, all or everybody as we see it under this order.","start":1537.763,"stop":1552.841,"duration":15.08}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's a group.","start":1552.841,"stop":1555.147,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"I imagine a group would be two or more people that have some type of club relation between them, and that would be up to the two or more people to determine what that was.","start":1555.147,"stop":1564.587,"duration":9.44},{"text":"I guess three of us could form a group.","start":1564.587,"stop":1567.489,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And there's nothing in Judge Johnson’s order that sheds any light on what he may have meant by using those words?","start":1567.489,"stop":1574.572,"duration":7.08}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Not that I can see, if the Court please.","start":1574.572,"stop":1576.733,"duration":2.16},{"text":"There’s nothing in his order that discusses any type of use or how they go about people and I think Judge Clark, in the Fifth Circuit order, points that out.","start":1576.733,"stop":1591.026,"duration":14.29}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, tell me Mr. Phelps. Getting back to what Mr. Justice White asked you earlier.","start":1591.026,"stop":1596.823,"duration":5.8},{"text":"Really, to decide this case, doesn’t one have to go back to the 1959 order and it’s underpinning at that time?","start":1596.823,"stop":1607.015,"duration":10.19}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"I think this, Mr. Justice Brennan, we have to see, of course, the -- there was an order to prohibit segregation in municipal recreational facilities.","start":1607.015,"stop":1619.393,"duration":12.38}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And that was the 1959 order.","start":1619.393,"stop":1621.169,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right, sir.","start":1621.169,"stop":1622.683,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And might want to look at this 19, what is it 1970 or 1971 order of Judge Johnson as simply a sequel, a supplement, as a further remedy to address the situation that he found in 1959?","start":1622.683,"stop":1638.599,"duration":15.92}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"I think so.","start":1638.599,"stop":1639.24,"duration":0.64},{"text":"I think it has to be looked at in the context though, Mr. Justice Brennan, that no resegregation has been written to in any stage and I think the record is barren of any support of resegregation.","start":1639.24,"stop":1650.847,"duration":11.61}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what I meant to suggest was and perhaps it doesn’t stand up, but what I meant to suggest was if it were that this later order is simply a supplement to the original order, then the issue of re-segregation is rather irrelevant, isn’t it?","start":1650.847,"stop":1671.733,"duration":20.89}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"I’m not sure I understand.","start":1671.733,"stop":1673.185,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don’t see what resegregation -- if this later order is just a further order adding to the 1959 order, in order to give effect to the 1959 order, then this issue of resegregation --","start":1673.185,"stop":1689.002,"duration":15.82}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me say this.","start":1689.002,"stop":1690.35,"duration":1.35},{"text":"I don’t feel that this present order is even germane really --","start":1690.35,"stop":1693.679,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":1693.679,"stop":1694.164,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to the 1969 order because that opened everything up, and now they have come along and the petitioners ask that it should be closed to a particular group because of the racial admissions policy of that particular group.","start":1694.164,"stop":1707.118,"duration":12.95}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then why did you -- do you concede that the Court of Appeals was correct in affirming Judge Johnson with respect to the school?","start":1707.118,"stop":1716.393,"duration":9.28}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1716.393,"stop":1718.328,"duration":1.93},{"text":"We make no issue about private schools in this proceeding.","start":1718.328,"stop":1721.531,"duration":3.2},{"text":"We don’t make that it’s even an issue.","start":1721.531,"stop":1723.949,"duration":2.42},{"text":"The affirmative duty on the school boards and the municipality to this --","start":1723.949,"stop":1728.74,"duration":4.79}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You agree the city may not make public recreational facilities available to a private school in the manner that they can make it available to a private club?","start":1728.74,"stop":1742.856,"duration":14.12}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that it would.","start":1742.856,"stop":1744.179,"duration":1.32},{"text":"Well, let me --","start":1744.179,"stop":1744.41,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that a yes or no question?","start":1744.41,"stop":1747.493,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"I’m not sure, sir.","start":1747.493,"stop":1748.469,"duration":0.98},{"text":"I’m not sure.","start":1748.469,"stop":1748.89,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Court of Appeals, well assume you say you agree, said that the city may not make its recreational facilities available on an exclusive basis even periodically to a private segregated school, whether it has a racial discriminatory policy or it is just all-white, isn’t it?","start":1748.89,"stop":1772.481,"duration":23.59}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1772.481,"stop":1773.326,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s what it -- and you have said you agree with that?","start":1773.326,"stop":1775.521,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"We do not contest that.","start":1775.521,"stop":1776.923,"duration":1.4},{"text":"We think that’s within (Voice Overlap).","start":1776.923,"stop":1778.853,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, why is the situation different with respect to a private club that has an expressed discriminatory policy?","start":1778.853,"stop":1784.822,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the city, as we understand it, has no affirmative duty to maintain desegregated or --","start":1784.822,"stop":1791.45,"duration":6.63}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it has an affirmative duty because it is a -- has -- it is under an order of the Federal District Court affirmatively to deseg -- to quit discriminating.","start":1791.45,"stop":1801.951,"duration":10.5},{"text":"It's under an order.","start":1801.951,"stop":1803.223,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the 1959 order.","start":1803.223,"stop":1804.826,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1804.826,"stop":1805.872,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And you're still subject to that order?","start":1805.872,"stop":1807.37,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, and we say we abide --","start":1807.37,"stop":1808.804,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And it may be that generally, absent such an order, you -- the city -- the pure neutrality would be unexceptionable.","start":1808.804,"stop":1821.034,"duration":12.23},{"text":"But if they are under an affirmative duty, under an order, how do you distinguish between schools and clubs?","start":1821.034,"stop":1826.475,"duration":5.44}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":1826.475,"stop":1827.565,"duration":1.09},{"text":"I read the 1959 order to say open up your recreational facilities.","start":1827.565,"stop":1834.023,"duration":6.46},{"text":"Open them up without regard to race or color.","start":1834.023,"stop":1837.543,"duration":3.52},{"text":"Don’t keep any group out --","start":1837.543,"stop":1838.322,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And keep them open.","start":1838.322,"stop":1839.774,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":1839.774,"stop":1840.28,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And keep them open.","start":1840.28,"stop":1841.385,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right, and keep them open, and don’t turn a Negro group away or a White group away.","start":1841.385,"stop":1847.95,"duration":6.57},{"text":"And, I don’t think that the 1959 order or any court of this -- or any decision of this Court puts a burden on a municipality to delve in to the racial composition to these groups.","start":1847.95,"stop":1859.45,"duration":11.5},{"text":"We think we are in strict accord with the 1959 order.","start":1859.45,"stop":1862.015,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Because you are not running from the order, but you do have to inquire about the school?","start":1862.015,"stop":1867.722,"duration":5.71}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1867.722,"stop":1868.415,"duration":0.69},{"text":"I think you have to do this.","start":1868.415,"stop":1869.075,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Private schools.","start":1869.075,"stop":1870.351,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"I think you have to go into the racial composition there because it -- we have to see that desegregated education is not interfered with and not retarded as this Court pointed out in Norwood versus Harrison.","start":1870.351,"stop":1884.267,"duration":13.92},{"text":"But I don’t think that government at any level should be placed with responsibility of delving into the membership policies of church clubs, social clubs, and political organizations.","start":1884.267,"stop":1895.39,"duration":11.12},{"text":"We think that -- we don’t plead that the 1959 order of Watson versus Memphis or any other decision requires us to do that.","start":1895.39,"stop":1902.493,"duration":7.1},{"text":"Now, I’d like to say this.","start":1902.493,"stop":1905.181,"duration":2.69},{"text":"Mr. Levin says that Montgomery, Alabama should be treated apart from other parts of the country.","start":1905.181,"stop":1912.274,"duration":7.09},{"text":"He says that, for some reason, there’s something different about the situation here.","start":1912.274,"stop":1920.333,"duration":8.06},{"text":"This community and in this area struggled with problems of desegregation and removal of discriminatory practices, and we feel that when we come before this Court and say that we are open, that our facilities are open to all, that’s not an empty promise or just a statement, its documented by the facts as they exist right in Montgomery.","start":1920.333,"stop":1942.801,"duration":22.47},{"text":"For example, two members of the respondent board that are before this Court today are black leaders in Montgomery.","start":1942.801,"stop":1951.401,"duration":8.6},{"text":"They were appointed without any court compulsion and they’re there and a part of this case.","start":1951.401,"stop":1960.062,"duration":8.66},{"text":"A black man is presently the Recreation Director for the entire program.","start":1960.062,"stop":1964.237,"duration":4.18},{"text":"There had been extensive construction of facilities throughout the City of Montgomery.","start":1964.237,"stop":1968.987,"duration":4.75},{"text":"Some by virtue of the joint proposal filed in 1970 and 1971, and some go far beyond that.","start":1968.987,"stop":1976.252,"duration":7.26},{"text":"It’s without dispute and they don’t dispute this in their reply briefs that Montgomery is commencing the construction of a municipal golf course with swimming pools being opened, that will be available to black people and white people and without -- everyone without regard to race or color.","start":1976.252,"stop":1995.137,"duration":18.88},{"text":"There is desegregated participation in municipally sponsored recreational activities.","start":1995.137,"stop":1999.977,"duration":4.84},{"text":"As pointed out in the portions of the record that he did not include and also in the appendix itself of the -- on pages 55 and 53.","start":1999.977,"stop":2011.576,"duration":11.6},{"text":"Seventeen of those 31 football games involved desegregated teams playing desegregated teams.","start":2011.576,"stop":2018.719,"duration":7.14},{"text":"The August 1st stipulated facts on which this record is before this Court says and states and agrees between the parties that all recreational facilities throughout the City of Montgomery are open to all on an equal basis with all person to other community have an equal access thereto without regard to raise the (Inaudible).","start":2018.719,"stop":2036.192,"duration":17.47},{"text":"That’s not just an empty statement, if the Court pleases.","start":2036.192,"stop":2039.028,"duration":2.84},{"text":"It’s supported by the actual facts that are living and existing in Montgomery, Alabama today.","start":2039.028,"stop":2045.239,"duration":6.21},{"text":"A comparison of the style of this case, from the appendix of how it started out with the parties that are there now, show that there had been a complete change in the Park and Recreation Board.","start":2045.239,"stop":2056.281,"duration":11.04},{"text":"We’ve got a new mayor.","start":2056.281,"stop":2057.687,"duration":1.41},{"text":"We’ve got new members and a Biracial Park and Recreation Board there in Montgomery.","start":2057.687,"stop":2062.42,"duration":4.73},{"text":"The leadership now in this area is coming from biracial groups.","start":2062.42,"stop":2066.676,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Doesn’t Judge Johnson live in Montgomery?","start":2066.676,"stop":2068.976,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2068.976,"stop":2069.592,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Doesn’t he know all of that?","start":2069.592,"stop":2071.06,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2071.06,"stop":2073.089,"duration":2.03},{"text":"I think that he does.","start":2073.089,"stop":2074.197,"duration":1.11},{"text":"I think, in answer to Mr. Justice Marshall’s comment, that he decided this case prior to this Court’s decision in Irvis.","start":2074.197,"stop":2084.679,"duration":10.48},{"text":"I think he thought that if a group had a policy of allowing only blacks or only whites in that in that it's in and if itself as a matter of law.","start":2084.679,"stop":2096.364,"duration":11.68}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree Montgomery is on the race question.","start":2096.364,"stop":2098.754,"duration":2.39},{"text":"I mean, Judge Johnson knew that but he still put this over us?","start":2098.754,"stop":2102.075,"duration":3.32}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes and what I say to the Court is true.","start":2102.075,"stop":2104.813,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2104.813,"stop":2106.256,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, these facts are true, if the Court please.","start":2106.256,"stop":2109.13,"duration":2.87},{"text":"We’ve got these participants down there and we state to the Court that discrimination in recreation in Montgomery, Alabama, as Mr. Justice Brennan mentioned in the 1969 order, we say we are in strict compliance with it.","start":2109.13,"stop":2127.297,"duration":18.17},{"text":"Any discrimination on behalf of the City of Montgomery, Alabama has been removed.","start":2127.297,"stop":2132.135,"duration":4.84},{"text":"We respectfully submit to the Court “root and branch.”","start":2132.135,"stop":2135.918,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Phelps, the electronic system is not functioning again today.","start":2135.918,"stop":2139.886,"duration":3.97},{"text":"You have two minutes left.","start":2139.886,"stop":2141.673,"duration":1.79},{"text":"There won’t be any light signal.","start":2141.673,"stop":2147.07,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Marshall, the District Court in the order that’s before this Court made the finding that the respondents allow all persons and groups to use recreational facilities specifically, and I quote, Judge Johnson.","start":2147.07,"stop":2159.957,"duration":12.89}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Why did he issue the order?","start":2159.957,"stop":2161.368,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"I don’t know, sir.","start":2161.368,"stop":2162.296,"duration":0.93},{"text":"I think because he understood the law to be that we had to go into the racial composition and see what kind of admissions policies, all the types of --","start":2162.296,"stop":2169.711,"duration":7.41}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he say that?","start":2169.711,"stop":2171.542,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Joseph D. Phelps","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2171.542,"stop":2171.81,"duration":0.27},{"text":"He said this, and I quote, “The City of Montgomery makes football, basketball and baseball facilities available to all on a non-discriminatory basis to private, to any private groups who apply for them on a non-discriminatory basis.”","start":2171.81,"stop":2184.788,"duration":12.98},{"text":"I agree with you, sir that the District Court does know that we have got two black members on the Board and it comes out and publicized in the press that a black man is heading all of the recreational programs throughout the City of Montgomery.","start":2184.788,"stop":2199.049,"duration":14.26},{"text":"Now, in conclusion, let me say this.","start":2199.049,"stop":2201.925,"duration":2.88},{"text":"They want to use the vehicle of this desegregation case to go into all of the admissions policies of various groups regardless of the size, composition, or purpose of the group.","start":2201.925,"stop":2214.662,"duration":12.74},{"text":"We don’t feel, in this case, on remand or otherwise that this is a proper vehicle to do it.","start":2214.662,"stop":2221.167,"duration":6.51},{"text":"The head of a group that they brought before the court is the YMCA, and the court found YMCA really wasn’t private because they are all encompassing membership and therefore, and the connection that the city and the white cooperating, an order was entered.","start":2221.167,"stop":2237.724,"duration":16.56},{"text":"If they have any examples that they feel like the city is using or using the city for subterfuge, those part is -- they are just -- as Mr. Justice Black said in Palmer versus Thompson, ought to be before the court.","start":2237.724,"stop":2250.828,"duration":13.1},{"text":"We respectfully submit to the Court that the two he mentions today, the Babe Ruth and the Dixie League, are not discriminatory as is evidenced by the portions of the depositions that he didn’t include.","start":2250.828,"stop":2263.13,"duration":12.3},{"text":"But this case is not the vehicle, we respectfully submit, to go in and to put a municipality on the basis of defending its relation with all types of private groups.","start":2263.13,"stop":2274.934,"duration":11.8},{"text":"We think that in Burton, the Court envisioned a shifting and analysis of circumstances and with the broad spectrum that they seek here, we say that this case is not the vehicle.","start":2274.934,"stop":2287.863,"duration":12.93},{"text":"As Mr. Justice -- Chief Justice Burger stated in Norwood versus Harrison, no presumptions flow from mere allegations.","start":2287.863,"stop":2295.015,"duration":7.15},{"text":"No one can be required, consistent with due process, to prove absence of violation of the law.","start":2295.015,"stop":2299.906,"duration":4.89},{"text":"If they’ve got a specific, they’ve got judicial retorts, but better than that, better than that if they’ve got something that they feel like is re-segregating, if they will bring it to the attention of the Park and Recreation Board of the City of Montgomery, if they will bring it to the attention of the Biracial Park and Recreation Board, I think it’ll be remedied and I state that it‘ll be remedied without the necessity of judicial intervention.","start":2299.906,"stop":2324.025,"duration":24.12},{"text":"I think that’s the posture of this case.","start":2324.025,"stop":2326.494,"duration":2.47},{"text":"That’s the posture of what Montgomery, Alabama is trying to do.","start":2326.494,"stop":2329.655,"duration":3.16},{"text":"We’ve made progress.","start":2329.655,"stop":2330.897,"duration":1.24},{"text":"He says in his brief “we applaud it.”","start":2330.897,"stop":2332.994,"duration":2.1},{"text":"We are proud of the progress that we’ve made.","start":2332.994,"stop":2335.611,"duration":2.62},{"text":"We think that the facts are undisputed and documented speak for themselves that public recreational, public recreational facilities in Montgomery, Alabama are open to all without regard to race or color and we ask this court to allow us to continue to keep them opened up.","start":2335.611,"stop":2353.989,"duration":18.38},{"text":"Thank you.","start":2353.989,"stop":2354.857,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, gentlemen.","start":2354.857,"stop":2356.024,"duration":1.17},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":2356.024,"stop":2357.972,"duration":1.95}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Jan  15 - 16, 1974","petitioner":"Gilmore","respondent":"City of Montgomery","docket":"72-1517","citation":"417 US 556 (1974)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/417/556","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 17, 1974"}